  "text": "Photo by Schoolhouse Maximalism isn’t about more clutter—it’s about more character. And in a small space, the best place to start? Right on the wall. Wall sconces are the secret weapon designers reach for again and again: they save space, layer in light, and (in some cases) double as sculptural art. In the cozy corners and clever placements ahead, we’re taking cues from some of our favorite designer spaces to show how a well-placed sconce can turn even the tiniest nook into a major design moment. Ready to see why they’re a small-space essential? Below, you’ll find out how to use them just like the pros. Photo by Lindsay Brown Big Style, Small Footprint Wall sconces are like magic for tiny rooms. They save surface space (goodbye, crowded nightstand), add ambient light, and double as design elements. The right sconce doesn’t just light a space, it defines it. Tip: Install them above a side table or next to the bed to free up surfaces and add character. Even better? Opt for a punch of bold color to liven things up and make more of a statement. Can’t hardwire? No problem. Plug-in sconces are a thing, and they look just as polished. Photo by Kerri Torrey Make It Count Don’t have space for a full-on gallery wall? A single sconce can make just as much of an impact. Use one to anchor a cozy reading nook, highlight a framed photo, or illuminate your kitchen counter. We like to think of it as jewelry for your walls. Tip: Pick a playful shape or bold color to turn a blank spot into a design moment. Photo by Amy Pigliacampo Double the Drama If you do have a little extra room, go for a pair. A matching pair of sconces flanking a mirror, mantle, or cozy reading nook adds instant symmetry (and the perfect amount of light). Tip: Don’t be afraid to think outside the box. Try flanking a kitchen window, framing a bathroom mirror, or highlighting a built-in bookshelf. Using matching sconces where you wouldn’t expect them adds a playful twist (plus, they bring balanced light to often overlooked corners). Max Out the Mix One of the best things about maximalism? You don’t have to choose just one vibe. Combine warm brass with a cool ceramic shade, or opt for a brightly colored fixture in an otherwise neutral space. Wall sconces are a low-commitment way to test out new textures and tones. Tip: Keep the palette cohesive, but don’t be afraid to have a little fun. Placement = Personality Sure, sconces work by the bed—but they can shine just about anywhere. Over a kitchen sink? Absolutely. In a hallway? Yes, please. Next to a bookshelf? Perfection. Small spaces thrive on big ideas. Tip: Use unexpected placement to create little moments of magic around your home. Photo by Kerri Torrey What are you favorite lighting tricks for small spaces? Lead Copywriter at Schoolhouse. Popular on Food52",
